                    <li>יחבלו במעמד הפיננסי שלך וישדדו חשבונות משותפים</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>כל שעה שבה אתה נשאר חשוף היא שעה שבה אתה מסתכן באיבוד שליטה.</strong></p>
                <p>מונעים דליפות, שומרים על קבצים ו-Email, מייצבים משא ומתן ומוניטין. תקבלו תעודת הקשחה חתומה לתיק.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="real-risk" aria-label="How the threat actually arrives">
            <div class="container">
                <h2>The Threat is Already Inside</h2>
                <p class="real-risk-intro">In most small business partnerships, access is never formally managed. It is granted in trust, built up over years, and never revisited — until the moment someone leaves and you discover what "shared access" meant in practice.</p>
                <div class="vignette-grid">

                    <div class="vignette">
                        <span class="vignette-app">WhatsApp Business Group</span>
                        <h3>The group nobody cleaned</h3>
                        <p>Three partners had run a business WhatsApp group for three years — vendors, logistics updates, pricing decisions. When one partner left, nobody removed him. Two months later, a new supplier negotiation started in the same group. He was still in it, reading every message, watching the margin discussions unfold in real time. By the time either of the remaining partners noticed, he had already approached the same supplier.</p>
                        <span class="vignette-source">Based on a true case, details obfuscated to protect the identities of those involved.</span>
                    </div>

                    <div class="vignette">
                        <span class="vignette-app">Google Drive</span>
                        <h3>The folder link that never expired</h3>
                        <p>They had shared a Google Drive folder at the start of the partnership — "for the project." The link was still active three years later. After the split, the departing partner could see every new file added to it: updated pricing sheets, new client proposals, a draft of the legal strategy their attorney had uploaded for review. Nobody had thought to revoke a link that had always just worked.</p>
                        <span class="vignette-source">Based on a true case, details obfuscated to protect the identities of those involved.</span>
                    </div>

                    <div class="vignette">
                        <span class="vignette-app">Personal Gmail as Business Email</span>
                        <h3>The account that ran the business</h3>
                        <p>The company had started with one partner's personal Gmail. Both partners had the password — it was practical at the time. After the dispute started, the departing partner still had full access to four years of business correspondence: every client email, every vendor negotiation, every conversation with the company attorney about the split itself. The password had never been changed because there had never been a reason to.</p>
                        <span class="vignette-source">Based on a true case, details obfuscated to protect the identities of those involved.</span>
                    </div>

                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

